<hr />
<dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
  <a name="spennant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">S (or SAFETY AFLOAT) PENNANT </dt>
  <dd>In US naval usage, a triangular pennant that is flown (from the port or starboard 
  yardarm when in port) to indicate that the vessel has won an annual safety award 
  competition (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva9.html#awardflag">award flag</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1351.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1351.gif" alt="[safety pennant]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br /><em>Safety Afloat Pennant, USN (<a href="http://mysite.verizon.net/vzeohzt4/Seaflags/awards/awards.html#safety">seaflags</a>)</em>
  </dd>
  
    <hr />
  <a name="sable"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SABLE </dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for black � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt1.html#tincture">tinctures</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr6.html#ruletincture">rule of tincture</a>&rsquo;).
    <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d555g.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d555g.gif" alt="[colour example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <p>
  <em>Please note that this term has a wider use than is detailed above, and the Editors recommend that a heraldic dictionary be consulted if further details are required.</em>
  </dd>

  <hr />
  <a name="saber"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SABRE (or SABER)</dt>
  <dd>In UK and US tradition and some others, a sword with a full handguard, and a curved single-edged blade 
  (originally) designed for use by mounted troops � but see note below.    <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2702.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2702.gif" alt="[saber example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2702a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2702a.gif" alt="[saber example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4054.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4054.gif" alt="[saber example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>

  <br>
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="pl-lu-cc.html">Cyc�w</a>, Poland (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="pl-ma-kw.html">Kowala</a>, Poland (fotw)</em>
  <p>
  <em>Please note that in some Central and East European usage the term is used to describe a sword with a curved single-edged blade but with a straightforward 
  cross guard as illustrated below � but see &lsquo;<a href="#scimitar">scimitar</a>&rsquo;.</em>
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4507.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4507.gif" alt="[saber example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4508.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4508.gif" alt="[saber example]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br><em>
  Flag of <a href="ua-vi-07.html">Illinetsi District</a>, Ukraine (fotw); 
  Arms of <a href="ua-08022.html">Nalyvaikivka</a>, Ukraine (fotw)</em> </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="safeconduct"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SAFE CONDUCT FLAG </dt>
  <dd>1) A special flag of internationally recognized design &ndash; such as that of the 
  Red Cross, Red Crescent, Red Crystal and others &ndash; which (by international agreement) 
  protects personnel engaged in medical succour, ambulances, civil and field hospitals 
  and hospital ships against military action &ndash; a Geneva Convention flag, or flag 
  of protection (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi4.html#internationalflag">international flag</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs8.html#supranationalflag">supra-national flag</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>2) The Red Cross, Red Crescent, Red Crystal and other recognized flag designs 
  (together with arm brassards or painted symbols) are also used to indicate the 
  facilities and personnel of these organisations rendering aid to the survivors 
  and casualties of natural or human disasters (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvi4.html#internationalflag">international flag</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs8.html#supranationalflag">supra-national flag</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3578.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3578.gif" alt="IRCRC flags" border="0" width="108" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3581.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3581.gif" alt="IRCRC flags" border="0" width="108" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3582.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3582.gif" alt="IRCRC flags" border="0" width="108" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flags of the <a href="int-red.html">Red Cross</a>, <a href="int-red.html">Red Crescent</a> and
  <a href="int-redx.html">Red Crystal</a> (fotw)</em> </p>
  <p><em>Please note that on 8 December 2005 the International 
  Committee of the Red Cross adopted a Protocol (Protocol III) authorizing a red 
  crystal (diamond shape) as an additional non-religious and politically neutral 
  symbol, however, please also note that the flags of the Red Cross and of its associated 
  organizations are at the same time international flags, safe conduct, flags of 
  protection and Geneva 
  Convention flags.</em></p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="safetyflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SAFETY FLAG</dt>
  <dd>1) In Japanese usage one of several green and white flags symbolizing safe conditions in various situations 
  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#weatherflag">weather flag 2)</a>&rsquo;.   
  <br>2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb4.html#beachflag">beach flag</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#stormwarning">storm warning flag</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva1.html#airfieldsafetyflag">airfield safety flag</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr1.html#redflag">red flag 1)</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1930a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1930a.gif" alt="safety flag" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1930b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1930b.gif" alt="safety flag" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1930c.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1930c.gif" alt="safety flag" border="0" height="108"></a><br /><em>Safety Flag for <a href="jp_sfty.html#sft">General Use</a>, Japan (fotw); 
  <a href="jp_sfty.html#hlt">Health Flag</a>; Japan (fotw); 
  <a href="jp_sfty.html#has">Health and Safety Flag</a>, Japan (fotw)</em>
     
  <hr /><a name="sailingship"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SAILING SHIP (or SAILING VESSEL)</dt>
  <dd>1) In traditional English heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva3.html#ancientship">ancient ship</a>&rsquo;.   
  <br>2) In vexillology and in modern heraldry the terms for a wind-powered, sea-going vessel regardless of type
  &ndash; but see the notes below (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#galleon">galleon</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4624.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4624.gif" alt="sailing ship" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2684.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2684.gif" alt="sailing ship" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4237.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4237.gif" alt="sailing ship" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="de-wim.html">Wittmund</a>, Germany (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="hr-ri-ko.html">Kostrena</a>, Croatia (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="eg-g-dum.html">Dumyat</a> (Governorate), Egypt (fotw)</em>
  <p>
  <em>Notes<br>a) The term �sailing vessel� (as given in the alternative heading above) can include those which are designed for inshore/leisure activities such as sailing dinghies or yachts, however;
  <br>2) to individually list the many types these or other sailing vessels is 
  (properly speaking) beyond the remit of this dictionary, nonetheless, please see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc2.html#caravel">caravel</a>&rsquo; 
  with its following note, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc4.html#cog">cog</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvn2.html#nef">nef</a>&rsquo;.    
  </em>    
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2708a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2708a.gif" alt="sailing ship" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br><em>The Arms of <a href="pt-vls.html">Velas</a>, Portugal showing a caravel (fotw)</em> 
  </dd>
   
  <hr /><a name="sailorsmast"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SAILOR&rsquo;S MAST</dt>
  <dd>In largely German usage, a flag pole or mast (most often) erected ashore for the 
  multiple display of  barge or inland waterway related flags for decorative purposes, 
  and equipped with a long gaff and yard &ndash; a display mast or bargemen&rsquo;s association 
  display mast (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd4.html#dressship">dress ship</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#gaff">gaff</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs7.html#stayedmast">stayed mast</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-y.html#yard">yard</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><em>Please note that this term is a translation of the German 
  schiffermast, and that use of such masts seems to be restricted to associations of 
  bargemen or similar.</em></p></dd>
  <hr /><a name="standrew"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SAINT ANDREW&rsquo;S CROSS </dt>
  <dd>1) See &lsquo;<a href="#saltire">saltire</a>&rsquo;. </dd>
  <dd>2) A white saltire on a blue field &ndash; the national flag of 
  <a href="gb-scotl.html">Scotland</a> or the Scottish saltire (see also, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-s.html#stgeorge">St. George's Cross 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-s.html#stpatrick">St. Patrick's Cross</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-u.html#unionjack">union jack 1)</a>&rsquo;).</dd>
  <dd>3) A blue saltire on a white field &ndash; the naval ensign of the 
  <a href="ru.html">Russian Federation</a> (and formerly of the Russian Empire) 
  - a St. Andrew's ensign, Andreevski&#301;, Andreevsky or Ahndreeyeeskeey. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d857.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d857.gif" alt="Scotland" border="0" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d857a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d857a.gif" alt="Russian naval ensign" border="0" /></a>
  <br/><em>National Flag of Scotland (fotw); Naval Ensign 
  of Russia (fotw)</em>
  <p><em>Please note that whilst the term St George's Cross 
  generally refers only to a red cross on a white field, the Cross of St Andrew, 
  due to a tradition that the saint was crucified on a diagonal cross, has come 
  to be regarded by many as a saltire of any colour or metal on a field of any colour 
  or metal. Although this is considered inaccurate in English heraldic or vexillological 
  usage, it is common in countries and languages where a term equivalent to 
  &ldquo;<a href="#saltire">saltire</a>&rdquo; does not exist. </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="standrewensign"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SAINT ANDREW&rsquo;S ENSIGN</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="#standrew">St Andrew&rsquo;s cross 3)</a>&rsquo; above.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d857a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d857a.gif" alt="[Russian naval ensign]" border="0" height="108"></a><br />
  <em>Naval Ensign of Russia (fotw)</em>  </dd>
    
  <hr /><a name="stanthony"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">SAINT ANTHONY&rsquo;S CROSS</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvct.html#crosstau">cross tau</a>&rsquo; (also �<a href="vxt-dv-a.html#acorn">acorn 
  cross</a>�).<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1913.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1913.gif" alt="[St. Anthony's cross]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1913a.gif">
